H0.text: Normal faults are landforms most likely produced when two continental plates collide, causing the edges of the plates to be crumpled and uplifted.

H1.text: Mountain ranges are the landforms most likely to result when two continental plates collide, causing the edges of the plates to be crumpled and uplifted.

H2.text: U-shaped valleys are the most likely landform resulting from the crumpling and uplifting of the plate edges when two continental plates collide.

H3.text: Shield volcanoes are the landforms most likely formed when two continental plates collide, causing the edges of the plates to be crumpled and uplifted.

A4.text: Mountain formation in orogens is largely a result of crustal thickening.

A5.text: Subduction zones consume oceanic crust, thicken lithosphere, and produce earthquakes and volcanoes.
